###### Some useful networking commands ###############
ip addr   : Lists all network interfaces and their assigned IP addresses on the host.
ip route   : Displays the routing table, showing how the host directs traffic to different networks.
docker network ls   : Shows all Docker networks currently defined on the system.
docker network inspect <kind-network-name>   : Provides detailed configuration and connected containers for a specific Docker network (like the one KIND uses).

iptables,iptable rules, chain, NAT    ### Need to read more on this

###### How to clean up the IPtables rules containing stale IP address entries #########
Listed IPtables rules for port 8443 : iptables -L -t nat -n -v  | grep 8443
Took note of target in offending rules , identified the bad IP address, cleaned its references by deleting the each such rule from all Chains: iptables -t nat -D <chain-name> <rule-num>
Flushed the offending IPtables CHAIN relevant to target captured: iptables -t nat -F <chain-name>
Deleted the Iptables CHAIN as well: iptables -t nat -X <chain-name>
Later verified that all the offending iptables rules containing stale IP address dont exist anymore using : iptables -L -t nat -n -v  | grep 8443

To check OS details Linux:
cat /etc/os-release

netstat -antp # The command netstat -antp is used to display active network connections and listening ports


Common network errors:-
1.Packet loss
ping -c 5 google.com
mtr
2. Latency
3. DNS issue
nslookup google.com
4. Network Interface error : problems with NICs (network interface cards)

Network error codes:
4xx client errors, 
401: Unauthorized
403: Forbidden
404: Not found
5xx server errors
500: Internal server error
502: Bad Gateway
503: Service Unavialable
504: Gateway timeout
Note:- 1xx informational response, 2xx success, 3xx redirection


Application level network errors:
1. Time out errors
2. Connection refused
3. I/O timeout
4. Broken pipe
5. Network could not be establish
6. DNS resolution failed

Troubleshooting tools:
ping and traceroute
netsat
tcpdump
nslookup and dig
wireshark tool -> *.pcap files, statistics->conversations, DynamiteLab open source tool to visualize pcap files.

# To view consul service logs:-
journalctl -xeu consul -f
journalctl -xeu consul --since "5 hour ago" -f
journalctl -xeu consul --since "10 minute ago" -f
journalctl -xeu consul --since "2025-10-24 09:00" --until "2025-10-24 12:00"
journalctl -xeu consul --since "2025-10-24"

################################################## SYSTEM DETAILS ###############################################################################
# To know detailed information about your Linux operating system
cat /etc/os-release
# To know kernel version and architecture details
uname -a

# Linux distribution Vs Pacakge manager used
RHEL, CentOS, Fedora, Amazon Linux 2, Amazon Linux 2023  -  "yum"
Ubuntu, Debian  - "apt"

# To check when system was rebooted last time:-
who -b
uptime -s
last reboot

# To check DNS server details on a host:
cat /etc/resolv.conf

# To check Router/Gateway details on a host:
ip route
Note: Refer to the entry with pattern "default via X.X.X.X"

# To check the tcp ports i.e Show all connections (both listening and established)
netstat -antp
# To check the udp ports i.e Show all connections (both listening and established)
netstat -anup
# To check the both the tcp and udp ports i.e Show all connections (both listening and established)
netstat -antup
ss -tuln

################################################## CONNECTIVITY RELATED ###############################################################################
# To check connectivity to the server, whether server is reachable or not:
ping <ip-address>
ping <hostname>

# Tests TCP connectivity to a specific port
telnet <ip-address-or-hostname> <port>
telnet www.google.com 443

# Tests TCP and UDP connectivity to a specific port
nc -zv <ip-address-or-hostname> <port>
nc -zv www.google.com 443

# Scans open ports
nmap www.google.com
nmap 142.250.73.100

# Tests HTTP/HTTPS endpoints and APIs
curl http(s)://<hostname-or-url>:<port>/<endpoint>

# To check DNS server details on a host:
cat /etc/resolv.conf

# DNS resolution
nslookup www.google.com
dig www.google.com

# Shows routing path to a host but does not confirms whether the ip is reachable or not, for that you have to use ping, telnet commands etc
ip route get 142.250.73.132

# Show all routes on a host
ip route

################################################## PERFORMANCE RELATED ###############################################################################

# To check CPU and MEMORY:
top
vmstat -w 1

# To check free memory
free -h
Note: free - Memory that is completely unused — not touched by apps, buffers, or cache.
      available - Memory that is available for new applications — includes free + reclaimable cache/buffers.

# Shows DISK usage for all mounted filesystems.
df -h
# Shows disk usage only for the filesystem that contains the current directory
df -h .
# Shows how much space a specific folder or file is using.
du -hs /var/log
# This shows the disk usage of each top-level directory on the root filesystem.
sudo du -sh /* 2>/dev/null
# To know size of all directories under /var directory
sudo du -sh /var/* 2>/dev/null


# To check IOPS usage on host:
iostat
iostat -dx
Note: If iostat not available then run:
sudo yum install sysstat   # RHEL/CentOS
sudo apt install sysstat   # Debian/Ubuntu

# To check actual IOPS supported, ec2 ui -> Storage -> Click EBS Volumes -> There you'll see size,IOPS (operations per second) ,throughput (MB of data transferred in 1 second).

# Real-time network bandwidth monitoring for Linux.
iftop -n -P




